04914nam a22007815i 9781400824755DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008247557 a10.1515/97814008247552doi  a(DE-B1597)467572  a(OCoLC)946714175  a(OCoLC)999365787  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDC83.3b.P44 2001eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a272/.2/09447362211 aPegg, Mark Gregory, eauthor.14aThe Corruption of Angels :bThe Great Inquisition of 1245-1246 /cMark Gregory Pegg.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource :b1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Two Hundred and One Days -- t2. The Death of One Cistercian -- t3. Wedged between Catha and Cathay -- t4. Paper and Parchment -- t5. Splitting Heads and Tearing Skin -- t6. Summoned to Saint-Sernin -- t7. Questions about Questions -- t8. Four Eavesdropping Friars -- t9. The Memory of What Was Heard -- t10. Lies -- t11. Now Are You Willing to Put That in Writing? -- t12. Before the Crusaders Came -- t13. Words and Nods -- t14. Not Quite Dead -- t15. One Full Dish of Chestnuts -- t16. Two Yellow Crosses -- t17. Life around a Leaf -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY OF WORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn two hundred and one days between May 1, 1245, and August 1, 1246, more than five thousand people from the Lauragais were questioned in Toulouse about the heresy of the good men and the good women (more commonly known as Catharism). Nobles and diviners, butchers and monks, concubines and physicians, blacksmiths and pregnant girls--in short, all men over fourteen and women over twelve--were summoned by Dominican inquisitors Bernart de Caux and Jean de Saint-Pierre. In the cloister of the Saint-Sernin abbey, before scribes and witnesses, they confessed whether they, or anyone else, had ever seen, heard, helped, or sought salvation through the heretics. This inquisition into heretical depravity was the single largest investigation, in the shortest time, in the entire European Middle Ages. Mark Gregory Pegg examines the sole surviving manuscript of this great inquisition with unprecedented care--often in unexpected ways--to build a richly textured understanding of social life in southern France in the early thirteenth century. He explores what the interrogations reveal about the individual and communal lives of those interrogated and how the interrogations themselves shaped villagers' perceptions of those lives. The Corruption of Angels, similar in breadth and scope to Emmanuel Le Roy Ladurie's Montaillou, is a major contribution to the field. It shows how heretical and orthodox beliefs flourished side by side and, more broadly, what life was like in one particular time and place. Pegg's passionate and beautifully written evocation of a medieval world will fascinate a diverse readership within and beyond the academy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aAlbigenses. 0aInquisitionzFrancezLauragais. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400824755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400824755.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-de